# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-institute-of-chemical-engineers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The **American Chemical Society** (**ACS**) is a scientific society based in the United States that supports scientific inquiry in the field of chemistry.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Founded in 1876 at New York University, the ACS currently has more than 262,000 members at all degree levels and in all fields of chemistry, chemical engineering, and related fields.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] It is one of the world's largest scientific societies by membership.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS is a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization and holds a congressional charter under Title 36 of the United States Code.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Its headquarters are located in Washington, D.C., and it has a large concentration of staff in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS is a source of scientific information through its peer-reviewed scientific journals, national conferences, and the Chemical Abstracts Service.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Its publications division produces over 90 scholarly journals including the prestigious *Journal of the American Chemical Society*, as well as the weekly trade magazine *Chemical & Engineering News*.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS holds national meetings twice a year covering the complete field of chemistry and also holds smaller conferences concentrating on specific chemical fields or geographic regions.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The primary source of income of the ACS is the Chemical Abstracts Service, a provider of chemical databases worldwide.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS has student chapters in virtually every major university in the United States and outside the United States as well.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] These student chapters mainly focus on volunteering opportunities, career development, and the discussion of student and faculty research.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The organization also publishes textbooks, administers several national chemistry awards, provides grants for scientific research, and supports various educational and outreach activities.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] In 1874, a group of American chemists gathered at the Joseph Priestley House to mark the 100th anniversary of Priestley's discovery of oxygen.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Two years later, on April 6, 1876, during a meeting of chemists at the University of the City of New York (now New York University) the American Chemical Society was founded.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The society received its charter of incorporation from the State of New York in 1877.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Although Chandler was a likely choice to become the society's first president because of his role in organizing the society, New York University chemistry professor John William Draper was elected as the first president of the society because of his national reputation.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Draper was a photochemist and pioneering photographer who had produced one of the first photographic portraits in 1840.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Chandler would later serve as president in 1881 and 1889.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] In the ACS logo, originally designed in the early 20th century by Tiffany's Jewelers and used since 1909, a stylized symbol of a kaliapparat is used.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The *Journal of the American Chemical Society* was founded in 1879 to publish original chemical research.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] It was the first journal published by ACS and is still the society's flagship peer-reviewed publication.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] In 1907, Chemical Abstracts was established as a separate journal (it previously appeared within JACS), which later became the Chemical Abstracts Service, a division of ACS that provides chemical information to researchers and others worldwide.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] *Chemical & Engineering News* is a weekly trade magazine that has been published by ACS since 1923.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The society adopted a new constitution aimed at nationalizing the organization in 1890.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] In 1905, the American Chemical Society moved from New York City to Washington, D.C.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] ACS was reincorporated under a congressional charter in 1937.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Congress and signed by president Franklin D.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] ACS's headquarters moved to its current location in downtown Washington in 1941.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] ACS first established technical divisions in 1908 to foster the exchange of information among scientists who work in particular fields of chemistry or professional interests.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Divisional activities include organizing technical sessions at ACS meetings, publishing books and resources, administering awards and lectureships, and conducting other events.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The original five divisions were 1) organic chemistry, 2) industrial chemists and chemical engineers, 3) agricultural and food chemistry, 4) fertilizer chemistry, and 5) physical and inorganic chemistry.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] As of 2016, there are 32 technical divisions of ACS.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] This is the largest division of the Society.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] It marked its 100th anniversary in 2008.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The first Chair of the Division was Edward Curtis Franklin.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The Organic Division played a part in establishing Organic Syntheses, Inc. and Organic Reactions, Inc. and it maintains close ties to both organizations.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The symposia also honor national award winners, including the Arthur C.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Cope Award, Cope Scholar Award, James Flack Norris Award in Physical Organic Chemistry, Herbert C.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Brown Award for Creative Research in Synthetic Methods.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The Division helps to organize symposia at the international meeting called Pacifichem and it organizes the biennial National Organic Chemistry Symposium (NOS) which highlights recent advances in organic chemistry and hosts the Roger Adams Award address.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The Division also organizes corporate sponsorships to provide fellowships for PhD students and undergraduates.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] It also organizes the Graduate Research Symposium and manages award and travel grant programs for undergraduates.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Local sections were authorized in 1890 and are autonomous units of the American Chemical Society.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] They elect their own officers and select representatives to the national ACS organization.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Local sections also provide professional development opportunities for members, organize community outreach events, offer awards, and conduct other business.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The Rhode Island Section was the first local section of ACS, organized in 1891.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] There are currently 186 local sections of the American Chemical Society in all 50 states, the District of Columbia, and Puerto Rico.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] International Chemical Sciences Chapters allow ACS members outside of the U.S. to organize locally for professional and scientific exchange.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] There are currently 36 International Chemical Sciences Chapters.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] ACS states that it offers teacher training to support the professional development of science teachers so they can better present chemistry in the classroom, foster the scientific curiosity of our nation's youth and encourage future generations to pursue scientific careers.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] As of 2009, Clifford and Kathryn Hach donated $33 million to ACS, to continue the work of the Hach Scientific Foundation in supporting high school chemistry teaching.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The Society sponsors the United States National Chemistry Olympiad (USNCO), a contest used to select the four-member team that represents the United States at the International Chemistry Olympiad (IChO).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS Division of Chemical Education provides standardized tests for various subfields of chemistry.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The two most commonly used tests are the undergraduate-level tests for general and organic chemistry.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Each of these tests consists of 70 multiple-choice questions, and gives students 110 minutes to complete the exam.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS also approves certified undergraduate programs in chemistry.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] A student who completes the required laboratory and course work—sometimes in excess of what a particular college may require for its Bachelor's degree—is considered by the Society to be well trained for professional work.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS coordinates two annual public awareness campaigns, National Chemistry Week and Chemists Celebrate Earth Week, as part of its educational outreach.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Since 1978 and 2003 respectively, the campaigns have been celebrated with a yearly theme, such as "Chemistry Colors Our World" (2015) and "Energy: Now and Forever!" (2013).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The GCI was founded in 1997 as an independent non-profit organization, by chemists Joe Breen and Dennis Hjeresen in cooperation with the Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The Petroleum Research Fund (PRF) is an endowment fund administered by the ACS that supports advanced education and fundamental research in the petroleum and fossil fuel fields at non-profit institutions.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Several categories of grants are offered for various career levels and institutions.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The fund awarded more than $25 million in grants in 2007.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The PRF traces its origins to the acquisition of the Universal Oil Products laboratory by a consortium of oil companies in 1931.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The companies established a trust fund, The Petroleum Research Fund, in 1944 to prevent antitrust litigation tied to their UOP assets.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS was named the beneficiary of the trust.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The first grants from the PRF were awarded in 1954.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] In 2000, the trust was transferred to the ACS.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS established The American Chemical Society Petroleum Research Fund and the previous trust was dissolved.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The PRF trust was valued at $144.7 million in December 2014.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS International Activities is the birthplace of the ACS International Center, an online resource for scientists and engineers looking to study abroad or explore an international career or internship.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The site houses information on hundreds of scholarships and grants related to all levels of experience to promote scientific mobility of researchers and practitioners in STEM fields.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The Society grants membership to undergraduates as student members provided they can pay the $25 yearly dues.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Any university may start its own ACS Student Chapter and receive benefits of undergraduate participation in regional conferences and discounts on ACS publications.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The American Chemical Society administers 64 national awards, medals and prizes based on scientific contributions at various career levels that promote achievement across the chemical sciences.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS national awards program began in 1922 with the establishment of the Priestley Medal, the highest award offered by the ACS, which is given for distinguished services to chemistry.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Additional awards are offered by divisions, local sections and other bodies of ACS.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Nichols Medal Award was the first ACS award to honor outstanding researchers in the field of chemistry.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] It was established in 1903 by the ACS New York Section and is named for William H.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Nichols, an American chemist and businessman and one of the original founders of ACS.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Of the over 100 Nichols Medalists, 16 have subsequently been awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The Willard Gibbs Award, granted by the ACS Chicago Section, was established in 1910 in honor of Josiah Willard Gibbs, the Yale University professor who formulated the phase rule.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The Georgia Local Section of ACS has awarded the Herty Medal since 1933 recognizing outstanding chemists who have significantly contributed to their chosen fields.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] All chemists in academic, government, or industrial laboratories who have been residing in the southeastern United States for at least 10 years are eligible.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The New York Section of ACS also gives Leadership Awards.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The Leadership Awards are the highest honors given by the Chemical Marketing and Economic Group of ACS NY since December 6, 2012.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] They are presented to leaders of industry, investments, and other sectors, for their contributions to science, technology, engineering and mathematics (STEM) initiatives.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Roy Vagelos (Regeneron, Merck), Thomas M.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Connelly (DuPont) and Juan Pablo del Valle (Mexichem).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS also administers regional awards presented annually at regional meetings.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Ann Nalley Regional Award for Volunteer Service to the American Chemical Society, Regional Awards for Excellence in High School Teaching, and the Stanley C.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] Israel Regional Award for Advancing Diversity in the Chemical Sciences.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] ACS Publications is the publishing division of the ACS.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] It is a nonprofit academic publisher of scientific journals covering various fields of chemistry and related sciences.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] In addition to academic journals, ACS Publications also publishes *Chemical & Engineering News*, a weekly trade magazine covering news in the chemical profession, *inChemistry*, a magazine for undergraduate students, and *ChemMatters*, a magazine for high school students and teachers.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] However it has recently launched new open access journals and provided authors with open access publishing options.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] In 2006, Congress debated legislation that would have instructed the National Institutes of Health (NIH) to require all investigators it funded to submit copies of final, peer-reviewed journal articles to PubMed Central, a free-access digital repository it operates, within 12 months of publication.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] At the time the American Association of Publishers (of which ACS is a member) hired a public relations firm to counter the open access movement.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] In spite of publishers' opposition, the PubMed Central legislation was passed in December 2007 and became effective in 2008.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] As the open access issue has continued to evolve, so too has the ACS's position.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS has also introduced several open access publishing options for its journals, including providing authors the option to pay an upfront fee to enable free online access to their articles.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] In 2015, the ACS launched the first fully open access journal in the society's history, *ACS Central Science*.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS states that the journal offers the same peer-review standards as its subscription journals, but without publishing charges to either authors or readers.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] A second open access title, *ACS Omega*, an interdisciplinary mega journal, launched in 2016.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] In 2005, the ACS was criticized for opposing the creation of PubChem, which is an open access chemical database developed by the NIH's National Center for Biotechnology Information.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS raised concerns that the publicly supported PubChem database would duplicate and unfairly compete with their existing fee-based Chemical Abstracts Service and argued that the database should only present data created by the Molecular Libraries Screening Center initiative of the NIH.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS lobbied members of the United States Congress to rein in PubChem and hired outside lobbying firms to try to persuade congressional members, the NIH, and the Office of Management and Budget (OMB) against establishing a publicly funded database.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS was unsuccessful, and as of 2012 PubChem is the world's largest free chemical database.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS is also the only provider of a major scientific publication database (SciFinder) that imposes a restriction on the number of records that can be exported.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] None of the competing products, such as Web of Science (owned by Clarivate), Scopus (owned by Elsevier) and The Lens (owned by Cambia) have similar restrictions.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS has been involved in numerous lawsuits regarding access to its databases, trademark rights, and copyrighted material.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] In many of these cases, the ACS lost or ended up with an unenforceable judgement.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS was also found guilty in several lawsuits brought against the Society by its employees.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] In 2004, a group of ACS members criticized the compensation of former executive director and chief executive officer John Crum, whose total salary, expenses, and bonuses for 2002 was reported to be $767,834.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] The ACS defended the figure, saying that it was in line with that of comparable organizations, including for-profit publishers.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-chemical-society] As of 2016, two employees were reported to have a total compensation exceeding $900,000, while 694 had a compensation exceeding $100,000.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The **American Institute of Chemical Engineers** (**AIChE**) is a professional organization for chemical engineers.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] AIChE was established in 1908 to distinguish chemical engineers as professionals independent of chemists and mechanical engineers.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] By 2024, AIChE had over 60,000 members from over 110 countries (sources vary).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] There are over 350 active student chapters at universities worldwide.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Student chapters aim to provide networking opportunities in academia and industry as well as increase student involvement locally and nationally.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] This section consists of excerpts from a historical pamphlet written for the Silver Anniversary of the AICHE in 1932.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] In 1905, *The Chemical Engineer* rounded out its first year of publication with an editorial by its founder and prominent engineer, Richard K.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Meade, that propounded the question: "Why not the American Society of Chemical Engineers?" He went on to say: "The profession is now a recognized one and there are probably at least five hundred chemical engineers in this country".
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The mechanical, civil, electrical, and mining engineers in the United States each had already established a national society, so Meade's editorial was quite pertinent.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] But it took time for the idea to take root and Meade kept promoting it for the next two years.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Finally, in 1907, he issued a call for a preliminary meeting to be held in Atlantic City in June 1907.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Some early leaders of the profession, Charles F.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Sadtler, and Thorn Smith along with about a dozen others answered Meade's call and met in Atlantic City on June 21, 1907.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The meeting concluded with the formation of an organizing committee of six members: Charles F.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The organizing committee sent a letter in September 1908 to 600 men in the chemical profession in the United States and Canada asking for their opinions about forming a chemical engineering society.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Two hundred replies were received and 70-80% were favorable.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Many of the others believed the existing societies (especially the American Chemical Society) were sufficient and they did not favor forming a new society.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The organizing committee decided to hold a larger, open meeting at the Hotel Belmont in New York City at which those opposed to forming the new society could present their arguments and opinions.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Accordingly, they invited fifty men prominent in the chemical profession (including men who opposed the forming of a new society) to meet on January 18, 1908.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Twenty-one men attended the meeting and fourteen others expressed their views in letters.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] After much discussion, the meeting ended without reaching a definitive decision.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] However, it was agreed to have a mail vote (on whether or not to form a chemical engineering society) after a complete stenographic report of the meeting was printed and sent to the fifty men who had been invited to the meeting.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The mail vote resulted in 36 replies of which 22 were in the affirmative, 6 were negative, and 8 were neutral.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Based on those voting results, the organizing committee of six called for a full-fledged organizational meeting to be held in Philadelphia on June 22, 1908.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Meanwhile, the committee of six drafted a proposed constitution to be presented at that meeting.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] That meeting resulted in the official formation of the American Institute of Chemical Engineers, the adoption of a constitution, and the election of Samuel P.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Sadtler as the first president of the Institute.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Divisions and forums provide technical information, programming for AIChE's technical meetings, and awards and recognition to outstanding chemical engineers in their areas of expertise.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] They also provide opportunities for affiliation with top engineers in the general disciplines as well as in emerging fields like biotechnology and sustainability.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The prerequisite qualifications for election to any of the membership grades are available in the AIChE Bylaws.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] As new technology is developed, there is a need for experts to collaborate to achieve common goals.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] AIChE plays a major role through joint initiatives with industry, academia, and others.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] Little was born in Boston, Massachusetts, in 1863 and studied chemistry at MIT from 1881 to 1884.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] In 1901, he married Henrietta Rogers Anthony.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] He died August 1, 1935, in Northeast Harbor, Maine.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] He was the uncle of Royal Little (1896–1989), founder and chair of Textron, and considered to be the father of conglomerates.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] In 1886, he joined Richmond Paper Company in East Providence, Rhode Island, as a chemist, later becoming superintendent of a paper mill, and effectively recognised that the chemical engineering design was wrong: by correcting this, he came to his first patent.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] Further research and patents followed, mainly related to paper processing technology.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] He was joined by a colleague from Richmond Paper, Roger Griffin forming a new company in 1886, Little & Griffin, which was located in Boston where MIT was also located.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] Griffin and Little prepared a manuscript for *The Chemistry of Paper-making*, which was, for many years, an authoritative text in the field.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] The book had not been entirely finished when Griffin was killed in a laboratory accident in 1893.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] After this tragedy, Little carried on in the business alone for several years.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] During these years, he founded the Cellulose Products Company, demonstrating that cellulose acetate could be used in producing nonflammable wire insulation and artificial silk.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] The company didn't do well financially, and when it was dissolved, Eastman Kodak purchased the company's patents for the first nonflammable motion picture film and the Lustron Company bought the artificial silk patents becoming the only American manufacturer of acetate silk.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] He collaborated with MIT and William Hultz Walker of the MIT Chemistry department, forming a partnership, Little & Walker, which lasted from 1900 to 1905, while both MIT and Little's company were still located in Boston.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] The partnership dissolved in 1905 when Walker dedicated his full-time to being in charge of the new Research Laboratory of Applied Chemistry at MIT.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] Little continued on his own and formally incorporated the company, Arthur D.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] He conducted analytical studies, the precursor of the consulting studies for which the firm would later become famous.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] As chairman of the visiting committee of the department of chemistry and chemical engineering at MIT, he was responsible for the introduction of the Chemical Engineering Practice School.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] He also taught papermaking at MIT from 1893 to 1916.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] Little was president of the American Chemical Society for 1912–1914, and president of the American Institute of Chemical Engineers for 1919, and president of the Society of Chemical Industry 1928–29.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/arthur-dehon-little] In 1931, he was awarded the Perkin Medal.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Atlantic City comprises the second half of the Atlantic City-Hammonton metropolitan statistical area, which encompasses those cities and all of Atlantic County for statistical purposes.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Both Atlantic City and Hammonton, as well as the surrounding Atlantic County, are culturally tied to Philadelphia and constitute part of the larger Philadelphia metropolitan area, the nation's seventh-largest metropolitan area as of 2020.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] New Jersey voters legalized casino gambling in Atlantic City in 1976, and the first casino opened two years later.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] From 1921 to 2004, Atlantic City hosted the Miss America pageant, which later returned to the city from 2013 to 2018.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] As of the 2020 census, the city had a population of 38,497, a decline of 1,061 (−2.7%) from the 2010 census count of 39,558, which in turn reflected a decrease of 959 (−2.4%) from the 40,517 counted in the 2000 census.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The city was incorporated on May 1, 1854, from portions of Egg Harbor Township and Galloway Township.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] It is located on Absecon Island and borders Absecon, Brigantine, Egg Harbor Township, Galloway Township, Pleasantville, Ventnor City, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Prior to Atlantic City's founding, the region served as a summer home for the Lenape, a Native American tribe.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] While the date of European settlement in present-day Atlantic City is not precisely determined, it is commonly thought that it was in 1783, when Jeremiah Leeds built and occupied a year-round home there.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In 1850, present-day Atlantic City was developed into a resort town.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Three years later, in early 1853, it was named Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Because of its location in South Jersey, which hugs the Atlantic Ocean between marshlands and islands, Atlantic City was then viewed by developers as prime real estate and a potential resort town.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In 1853, the city's first commercial hotel, the Belloe House, was built at the intersection of Massachusetts and Atlantic Avenues.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The following year, in 1854, the city was incorporated.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The same year, train service began on the Camden and Atlantic Railroad.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Built on the edge of the bay, this served as the direct link of this remote parcel of land with Philadelphia, the second-most populous city in the United States at the time and the largest city in Pennsylvania.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The same year, construction of the Absecon Lighthouse, designed by George Meade of the Corps of Topographical Engineers, was approved, with work initiated the next year.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] By 1874, almost 500,000 passengers a year were coming to Atlantic City by rail.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In *Boardwalk Empire: The Birth, High Times, and Corruption of Atlantic City*, "Atlantic City's Godfather" Jonathan Pitney, known as the "Father of Atlantic City", initially sought to develop Atlantic City as a health resort.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Pitney persuaded municipal authorities that a railroad to the beach in Atlantic City would be beneficial.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The first boardwalk was built in 1870 along a portion of the beach in an effort to help hotel owners keep sand out of their lobbies.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Businesses were restricted and the boardwalk was removed each year at the end of the peak season.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Because of its effectiveness and popularity, the boardwalk was expanded in length and width, and modified several times in subsequent years.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Prior to the destructive 1944 Great Atlantic Hurricane, the historic length of the boardwalk was about 7 mi (11 km) and it extended from Atlantic City to Longport, through Ventnor and Margate.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The first road connecting the city to the mainland at Pleasantville was completed in 1870 and charged a 30-cent toll.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Albany Avenue was the first road to the mainland available without a toll.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] By 1878, because of the growing popularity of the city, one railroad line could no longer keep up with demand.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Soon, the Philadelphia and Atlantic City Railway was also constructed to transport tourists to Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] At this point massive hotels like the United States Hotel and Surf House, as well as smaller rooming houses, had sprung up all over town.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The United States Hotel took up a full city block between Atlantic, Pacific, Delaware, and Maryland Avenues.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] These hotels were not only impressive in size, but featured the most up-to-date amenities, and were considered quite luxurious for their time.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In 1883, salt water taffy was conceived in Atlantic City by David Bradley.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The traditional story is that Bradley's shop close to the beach was flooded with ocean water after a storm, soaking his taffy.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] He sold the "salt water taffy" to a girl, who walked down to the beach to show her friends.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Bradley's mother was in the back of the store when the sale was made, and loved the name, giving the candy its name.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In the early 20th century, Atlantic City experienced a radical building boom.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Many of the modest boarding houses that dotted the boardwalk were replaced with large hotels.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Two of the city's most distinctive hotels were the Marlborough-Blenheim Hotel and the Traymore Hotel.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Expansion of the city was driven by the relative ease of transport to and from Philadelphia.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The fastest express trains traveled from one end to the other in about an hour, whereas competing towns on the Jersey Shore required an additional 30–90 minutes each way.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In 1902, Josiah White III bought a parcel of land near Ohio Avenue and the boardwalk, where he started construction and built the Queen Anne style Marlborough House.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In 1905, he chose to expand the hotel and bought another parcel of land adjacent to his Marlborough House.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In an effort to make his new hotel a source of conversation, White hired the architectural firm of Price and McLanahan.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The firm made use of reinforced concrete, a new building material invented by Jean-Louis Lambot in 1848, and Joseph Monier received the patent in 1867.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The hotel's Spanish and Moorish themes, capped off with its signature dome and chimneys, represented a step forward from other hotels that had a classically designed influence.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] White named the new hotel the Blenheim and merged the two hotels into the Marlborough-Blenheim.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Bally's Atlantic City was later constructed at this location.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The Traymore Hotel was located at the corner of Illinois Avenue and the boardwalk.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Constructed in 1879 as a small boarding house, the hotel grew through a series of uncoordinated expansions.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] By 1914, the hotel's owner, Daniel White, Josiah White's half-brother, taking a hint from the Marlborough-Blenheim, commissioned the firm of Price and McLanahan to build an even bigger hotel to replace the original wooden structure.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Rising 16 stories, the tan brick and gold-capped hotel would become one of the city's best-known landmarks.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The hotel made use of ocean-facing hotel rooms by jutting its wings farther from the main portion of the hotel along Pacific Avenue.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] One by one, additional large hotels were constructed along the boardwalk, including the Brighton, Chelsea, Shelburne, Ambassador, Ritz Carlton, Mayflower, Madison House, and the Breakers.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The Quaker-owned Chalfonte House, opened in 1868, and Haddon House, opened in 1869, flanked North Carolina Avenue at the beach end.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Over the years, their original wood-frame structures would be enlarged, and even moved closer to the beach.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The modern Chalfonte Hotel, eight stories tall, opened in 1904.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The modern Haddon Hall was built in stages and was completed in 1929, at eleven stories.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] By this time, they were under the same ownership and merged into the Chalfonte-Haddon Hall Hotel, becoming the city's largest hotel with nearly 1,000 rooms.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] By 1930, The Claridge Hotel, the city's last large hotel constructed before the casino era, opened its doors.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The 480-room Claridge was built by a partnership that included renowned Philadelphia contractor John McShain.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] At 24 stories and 370 stone (5,200 lb; 2,300 kg) in height, it would become known as the "Skyscraper by the Sea".
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] With tourism peaking in the 1920s, the period is often considered by historians to be Atlantic City's golden age.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] During Prohibition, which was enacted nationally in 1919 and lasted until 1933, much liquor was consumed and gambling regularly took place in the back rooms of nightclubs and restaurants.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] During Prohibition, racketeer and political boss Enoch L.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Prohibition was largely unenforced in Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Because alcohol that had been smuggled into the city with the implicit approval of local officials, it was easily obtained at restaurants and other establishments, and the resort's popularity grew further.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The city then dubbed itself as "The World's Playground".
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Nucky Johnson's income, which reached as much as $500,000 annually, came from the kickbacks he took on illegal liquor, gambling and prostitution operating in the city, as well as from kickbacks on construction projects.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] During this time, Atlantic City was led by mayor Edward L.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Bader, known for his contributions to the construction, athletics and aviation of Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Despite opposition, he had Atlantic City purchase the land that became the city's municipal airport and high school football stadium, both of which were later named Bader Field in his honor.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] He led the initiative, in 1923, to construct the Atlantic City High School at Albany and Atlantic Avenues.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Bader, in November 1923, initiated a public referendum, during the general election, at which time residents approved the construction of a Convention Center.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The city passed an ordinance approving a bond issue for $1.5 million to be used for the purchase of land for Convention Hall, now known as the Boardwalk Hall, finalized on September 30, 1924.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Bader was also a driving force behind the creation of the Miss America competition.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In May 1929, Johnson hosted a conference for organized crime figures from all across America that created a National Crime Syndicate.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The men who called this meeting were Masseria family lieutenant Charles "Lucky" Luciano and former Chicago South Side Gang boss Johnny "the Fox" Torrio, with heads of the Bugs and Meyer Mob, Meyer Lansky and Benjamin Siegel, being used as muscle for the meeting.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Gangster and businessman Al Capone attended the conference and was photographed walking along the Atlantic City boardwalk with Johnson.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The 1930s through the 1960s were a heyday for nightclub entertainment.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Popular venues on the white-populated south side included the 500 Club, the Clicquot Club, and the Jockey Club.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In the Northside neighborhood, home to African Americans in the racially segregated city, a black entertainment district reigned on Kentucky Avenue.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Four major nightclubs, Club Harlem, the Paradise Club, Grace's Little Belmont, and Wonder Gardens, drew both black and white patrons.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] During the summer tourist season, jazz and R&B music could be heard into the wee hours of the morning.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Soul food restaurants and ribs joints also lined Kentucky Avenue, including Wash's Restaurant, Jerry's and Sap's.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Like many older East Coast cities after World War II, Atlantic City became plagued with poverty, crime, corruption, and general economic decline in the mid-to-late 20th century.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The neighborhood known as the "Inlet" became particularly impoverished.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The reasons for the resort's decline were multi-layered.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] First, the automobile became more readily available to many Americans after the war.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Atlantic City had initially relied upon visitors coming by train and staying for a couple of weeks.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The car allowed them to come and go as they pleased, and many people would spend only a few days, rather than weeks.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The advent of suburbia also played a significant role.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] With many families moving to their own private houses, luxuries such as home air conditioning and swimming pools diminished their interest in flocking to the luxury beach resorts during the hot summer.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Finally, the rise of relatively cheap jet airline service allowed visitors to travel to year-round resort places such as Miami Beach and the Bahamas.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The city hosted the 1964 Democratic National Convention which nominated Lyndon Johnson for president and Hubert Humphrey as vice president.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The convention and the press coverage it generated, however, cast a harsh light on Atlantic City, which by then was in the midst of a long period of economic decline.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Many felt that the friendship between Johnson and Governor of New Jersey Richard J.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Hughes led Atlantic City to host the Democratic Convention.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] By the late 1960s, many of the resort's once great hotels were suffering from high vacancy rates.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Most of them were either shut down, converted to cheap apartments, or converted to nursing home facilities by the end of the decade.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Prior to and during the advent of legalized gambling, many of these hotels were demolished.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The Breakers, The Chelsea, the Brighton, the Shelburne, the Mayflower, the Traymore and the Marlborough-Blenheim were demolished in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Of the many pre-casino resorts that bordered the boardwalk, only the Claridge, the Dennis, the Ritz-Carlton, and the Haddon Hall survive to this day as parts of Bally's Atlantic City, a condo complex, and Resorts Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The old Ambassador Hotel was purchased by Ramada in 1978 and was gutted to become the Tropicana Casino and Resort Atlantic City, only reusing the steelwork of the original building.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Smaller hotels off the boardwalk, such as the Madison also survived.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In an effort at revitalizing the city, New Jersey voters in 1976 passed a referendum, approving casino gambling for Atlantic City; this came after a 1974 referendum on legalized gambling failed to pass.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Immediately after the legislation passed, the owners of the Chalfonte-Haddon Hall Hotel began converting it into the Resorts International.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] It was the first legal casino in the eastern United States when it opened on May 26, 1978.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Other casinos were soon constructed along the Boardwalk and, later, in the marina district for a total of nine today.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The introduction of gambling did not, however, quickly eliminate many of the urban problems that plagued Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Many people have suggested that it only served to exacerbate those problems, as attested to by the stark contrast between tourism intensive areas and the adjacent impoverished working-class neighborhoods.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] While Atlantic City has been less popular than Las Vegas as a gambling city in the United States, other events such as live music, boxing matches, and performances like Cirque du Soleil became popular at hotel casinos.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Mike Tyson fought most of his fights in Atlantic City in the 1980s, which helped Atlantic City achieve national attention as a gambling resort and vacation destination.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Several highrise condominiums were built for use as permanent residences or second homes.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] By end of the decade, it was one of the most popular tourist destinations in the United States.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In 1999 the Atlantic City Redevelopment Authority partnered with Las Vegas casino mogul Steve Wynn to develop a new roadway to a barren section of the city near the Marina.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Nicknamed "The Tunnel Project", Steve Wynn planned the proposed 'Mirage Atlantic City' around the idea that he would connect the $330 million tunnel stretching 2.5 mi (4.0 km) from the Atlantic City Expressway to his new resort.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The roadway was later officially named the Atlantic City-Brigantine Connector, and funnels incoming traffic off of the expressway into the city's marina district and the city of Brigantine.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Although Wynn's plans for development in the city were scrapped in 2002, the tunnel opened in 2001.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The new roadway prompted Boyd Gaming in partnership with MGM/Mirage to build Atlantic City's newest casino.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Borgata opened in July 2003, and its success brought an influx of developers to Atlantic City with plans for building grand, Las Vegas-style mega casinos to revitalize the aging city.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Owing to economic conditions and the late 2000s recession, many of the proposed mega casinos never advanced further than the initial planning stage.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] One of these developers was Pinnacle Entertainment, which purchased the Sands Atlantic City for $250–$270 million and closed it on November 11, 2006 with plans to replace it with a larger casino.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The following year, the resort was demolished in an implosion, the first of its kind in Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] While Pinnacle Entertainment intended to replace it with a $1.5-$2-billion casino resort, the company canceled its construction plans and sold the land for $29.5 million.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] MGM Resorts International announced in October 2007 that it would pull out of all development for Atlantic City, effectively ending its plans for the MGM Grand Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In 2006, Morgan Stanley purchased 20 acres (8.1 ha) directly north of the Showboat Atlantic City for a new $2-billion-plus casino resort.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Revel Entertainment Group was named as the project's developer for the Revel Casino.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Revel was hindered with many problems, the biggest setback occurring in April 2010 when Morgan Stanley, the owner of 90% of Revel Entertainment Group, decided to discontinue funding for continued construction and put its stake in Revel up for sale.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Ultimately, Governor Chris Christie offered Revel $261 million in state tax credits to assist the casino once it opened.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Revel completed all of the exterior work and had continued work on the interior after finally receiving the funding necessary to complete construction, and had a soft opening in April 2012 before being fully open the next month.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Ten months later, in February 2013, after serious losses and a write-down in the value of the resort from $2.4 billion to $450 million, Revel filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] It was restructured but still could not carry on and re-entered bankruptcy on June 19, 2014.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] It was put up for sale, however as no suitable bids were received the resort closed its doors in September 2014.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The property was bought by AC Ocean Walk, LLC for $200 million in 2017, and reopened in 2018 as Ocean Casino Resort.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] On October 29, 2012, "Superstorm Sandy" struck Atlantic City and caused flooding and power-outages but left minimal damage to any of the tourist areas.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The storm produced an all-time record low barometric pressure reading of 943 mb (27.85") for not only Atlantic City, but the state of New Jersey.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In the wake of the closures and declining revenue from casinos, Governor Christie said in September 2014 that the state would consider a 2015 referendum to end the 40-year-old monopoly that Atlantic City holds on casino gambling and allowing gambling in other municipalities.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] With casino revenue declining from $5.2 billion in 2006 to $2.9 billion in 2013, the state saw a drop in money from its 8% tax on those earnings, which is used to fund programs for senior citizens and the disabled.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In May 2018, the United States Supreme Court ruled in *Murphy v.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] National Collegiate Athletic Association* that the Professional and Amateur Sports Protection Act was unconstitutional.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The act was overturned, allowing New Jersey to move ahead with plans to implement legalized sports betting.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Despite being the state to initiate the landmark ruling, New Jersey was actually the third state to legalize sports betting after Nevada and Delaware.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In June 2018, New Jersey governor Phil Murphy signed the legislation into law, and several New Jersey–based casino brands subsequently opened sportsbooks, especially in Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In 2019, the Atlantic City area had the highest rates of foreclosures in the nation.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] This has disproportionately affected Black residents in neighborhoods segregated by redlining, a legacy that is mirrored by the values of properties on the Monopoly game board.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] After several casino closures and the COVID-19 pandemic, strikes and pickets were being threatened in June 2022 by casino employees which were short-staffed and wanted pay raises.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In 2022, the New Jersey Economic Development Authority ranked Atlantic City second on its list of the state's food desert communities (behind Camden).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Atlantic City was one of a dozen municipalities statewide on the list where the entire municipality was a food desert community.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] As of 2024, there was only one functioning supermarket in Atlantic City, the Save-A-Lot food store located in Renaissance Plaza, an area of the city known for its significant homeless population and drug use.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The nearest full-service supermarket being located in neighboring Ventnor City, which is 3 miles (4.8 km) away from the majority of Atlantic City's population.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In an area with unemployment 50% above the statewide average and with 87% of area residents lacking a car, getting access to a supermarket for city residents has been difficult, requiring long rides on public transportation.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] To remedy this, proposals for a supermarket were floated beginning in May 2021, and Atlantic City's City Council authorized the Casino Reinvestment Development Authority to look for developers to build a supermarket.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The Casino Reinvestment Development Authority proposed a new supermarket that would be located on an empty parking lot behind the Tanger Outlets and near the Atlantic City Expressway.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Groundbreaking for a ShopRite supermarket had taken place in October 2021, after Village Super Market received $18.7 million from the Casino Reinvestment Development Authority to construct the store.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The supermarket was expected to be completed by December 2022, although no construction or building had happened on the site.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] After the time for the contract expired, the Casino Reinvestment Development Authority (CRDA) announced that the deal with Village Super Market was dead and that they were looking for new contenders.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] VSM created a new plan for CRDA and the city's Council to review and by July 2023, it and a Chinese conglomerate headquartered in Hong Kong emerged as the two candidates to build the supermarket.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The project, expected to be completed by the end of 2026, would increase the size of the existing store by 50% to more than 28,000 square feet (2,600 m2), allowing the expansion of fresh fruit, vegetable and meat options to shoppers.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] According to the United States Census Bureau, Atlantic City had a total area of 17.21 square miles (44.59 km2), including 10.76 square miles (27.87 km2) of land and 6.45 square miles (16.72 km2) of water (37.50%).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The city is located on 8.1 mi-long (13.0 km) Absecon Island, along with Ventnor City, Margate City and Longport to the southwest.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Atlantic City borders the Atlantic County municipalities of Absecon, Brigantine, Egg Harbor Township, Galloway Township, Pleasantville, and Ventnor City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The city is located 60 mi (97 km) southeast of Philadelphia and 125 mi (201 km) south of New York City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Unincorporated communities, localities and place names located partially or completely within the city include Chelsea, City Island, Great Island and Venice Park.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] According to the Köppen climate classification system, Atlantic City has a humid subtropical climate (*Cfa*) with warm, moderately humid summers, cool winters and year-around precipitation.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] During the summer months in Atlantic City, a cooling afternoon sea breeze is present on most days, but episodes of extreme heat and humidity can occur with heat index values at or above 95.0 °F (35.0 °C).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] During the winter months, episodes of extreme cold and wind can occur with wind chill values below 0.0 °F (−17.8 °C).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The plant hardiness zone at Atlantic City Beach is 8a with an average annual extreme minimum air temperature of 11.0 °F (−11.7 °C).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The average seasonal (November–April) snowfall total is 12 to 18 in (300 to 460 mm), and the average snowiest month is February which corresponds with the annual peak in nor'easter activity.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Kuchler U.S. potential natural vegetation types, Atlantic City would have a dominant vegetation type of Northern Cordgrass (*73*) with a dominant vegetation form of Coastal Prairie (*20*).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] As of the 2020 census, Atlantic City had a population of 38,497.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] 23.5% of residents were under the age of 18 and 15.8% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] For every 100 females there were 94.4 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 91.4 males age 18 and over.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] 99.9% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.1% lived in rural areas.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] There were 15,859 households in Atlantic City, of which 28.9% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Of all households, 24.2% were married-couple households, 28.5% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 40.3% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] About 40.2% of all households were made up of individuals and 16.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] There were 20,419 housing units, of which 22.3% were vacant.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The homeowner vacancy rate was 4.3% and the rental vacancy rate was 9.2%.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The 2010 United States census counted 39,558 people, 15,504 households, and 8,558 families in the city.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] There were 20,013 housing units at an average density of 1,862.2 per square mile (719.0/km2).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 30.45% (12,044) of the population.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Of the 15,504 households, 27.3% had children under the age of 18; 25.9% were married couples living together; 22.2% had a female householder with no husband present and 44.8% were non-families.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Of all households, 37.5% were made up of individuals and 14.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The average household size was 2.50 and the average family size was 3.34.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] For every 100 females, the population had 96.2 males.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] For every 100 females ages 18 and older there were 94.4 males.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The Census Bureau's 2006–2010 American Community Survey showed that (in 2010 inflation-adjusted dollars) median household income was $30,237 (with a margin of error of +/− $2,354) and the median family income was $35,488 (+/− $2,607).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] About 23.1% of families and 25.3% of the population were below the poverty line, including 36.6% of those under age 18 and 16.8% of those age 65 or over.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] As of the 2000 United States census, there were 40,517 people, 15,848 households, and 8,700 families residing in the city.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The population density was 3,569.8 inhabitants per square mile (1,378.3/km2).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] There were 20,219 housing units at an average density of 1,781.4 per square mile (687.8/km2).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The racial makeup of the city was 44.16% black or African American, 26.68% White, 0.48% Native American, 10.40% Asian, 0.06% Pacific Islander, 13.76% other races, and 4.47% from two or more races.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] 24.95% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] 19.44% of the population was non-Hispanic whites.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] There were 15,848 households, out of which 27.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 24.8% were married couples living together, 23.2% had a female householder with no husband present, and 45.1% were non-families.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] 37.2% of all households were made up of individuals, and 15.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The average household size was 2.46 and the average family size was 3.26.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] In the city the age distribution of the population shows 25.7% under the age of 18, 8.9% from 18 to 24, 31.0% from 25 to 44, 20.2% from 45 to 64, and 14.2% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] For every 100 females, there were 96.1 males.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 93.2 males.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The median income for a household in the city was $26,969, and the median income for a family was $31,997.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] Males had a median income of $25,471 versus $23,863 for females.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] The per capita income for the city was $15,402.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p01] About 19.1% of families and 23.6% of the population were below the poverty line, including 29.1% of those under age 18 and 18.9% of those age 65 or over.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] In September 2014, the greater Atlantic City area had one of the highest unemployment rates in the country at 13.8%, out of a labor force of around 141,000.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] In July 2010, Governor Chris Christie announced that a state takeover of the city and local government "was imminent".
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] In January 2011, Chris Christie announced the creation of the Atlantic City Tourism District, a state-run district encompassing the boardwalk casinos, the marina casinos, the Atlantic City Outlets, and Bader Field.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Fairleigh Dickinson University's PublicMind poll surveyed New Jersey voters' attitudes on the takeover.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] A February 2011 survey showed that 43% opposed the measure while 29% favored direct state oversight.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The poll also found that even South Jersey voters expressed opposition to the plan; 40% reported they opposed the measure and 37% reported they were in favor of it.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] On April 29, 2011, the boundaries for the state-run tourism district were set.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The district would include heavier police presence, as well as beautification projects and infrastructure improvements.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The CRDA would oversee all functions of the district and make changes to attract new businesses and attractions.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] New construction has already resulted in cases of eminent domain being used to seize properties for development.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The tourism district would comprise several key areas in the city: the Marina District, Ducktown, Chelsea, South Inlet, Bader Field, and Gardner's Basin.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Also included are 10 roadways that lead into the district, including several in the city's northern end, or North Beach.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Gardner's Basin, which is home to the Atlantic City Aquarium, was initially left out of the tourism district, while a residential neighborhood in the Chelsea section was removed from the final boundaries, owing to complaints from the city.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Also, the inclusion of Bader Field in the district was controversial and received much scrutiny from mayor Lorenzo Langford, who cast the lone "no" vote on the creation of the district citing its inclusion.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The history of gambling in Atlantic City traces back to Prohibition and the 1920s, with racketeer Louis Kuehnle running an underground hotel and casino.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Enoch "Nucky" Johnson followed and furthered Atlantic City's rise through the Roaring Twenties as a destination for drinking, gambling, and nightlife.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] In 1974, New Jersey voters voted 60%–40% against legalizing casino gambling at four sites statewide, but two years later approved by 56%–44% a new referendum which legalized casinos, but restricted them to Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Resorts Atlantic City was the first casino to open, in May 1978, with a ribbon-cutting ceremony featuring Governor of New Jersey Brendan Byrne.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Atlantic City is considered the "Gambling Capital of the East Coast", and currently has nine large casinos.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] In 2011, New Jersey's then 12 casinos employed approximately 33,000 employees, had 28.5 million visitors, made $3.3 billion in gaming revenue, and paid $278 million in taxes.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] They are regulated by the New Jersey Casino Control Commission and the New Jersey Division of Gaming Enforcement.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Executives at Trump Entertainment Resorts, whose sole remaining property at the time was the Trump Taj Mahal, said in 2013 that they were considering the option of selling the Taj and winding down and exiting the gaming and hotel business.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Trump Taj Mahal closed October 10, 2016, after failing to come to terms with union workers.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Caesars Entertainment executives have been reconsidering the future of their three remaining Atlantic City properties (Bally's, Caesars and Harrah's), in the wake of a Chapter 11 bankruptcy filing by the company's casino operating unit in January 2015.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] In 2020, Bally's Atlantic City was acquired by Bally's Corporation.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Gross gaming revenue of the city's nine operating casinos in 2022 totaled $2.79 billion, a 9% increase from the $2.55 billion earned the previous year.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] theme, was part of Bally's Atlantic City until 2020, when it became part of Caesars.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The Atlantic City Boardwalk opened on June 26, 1870, a temporary structure erected for the summer season that was the first boardwalk in the world.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] At 5+1⁄2 miles (8.9 km) long, the Atlantic City Boardwalk is also the world's longest and busiest boardwalk.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The Boardwalk starts at Absecon Inlet in the north and runs along the beach south-west to the city limit 4 mi (6.4 km) away then continues 1+1⁄2 mi (2.4 km) into Ventnor City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Casino/hotels front the boardwalk, as well as retail stores, restaurants, and amusements.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Notable attractions include the Boardwalk Hall, House of Blues, and the Ripley's Believe It or Not! museum.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] In October 2012, Hurricane Sandy destroyed the northern part of the boardwalk fronting Absecon Inlet, in the residential section called South Inlet.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The oceanfront boardwalk in front of the Atlantic City casinos survived the storm with minimal damage.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The first pier along the boardwalk, Applegate's Pier, opened in 1884.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Young in 1891, who expanded and operated it as Young's Ocean Pier, but it was mostly destroyed in a 1912 fire.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The remaining part of the pier was rebuilt in 1922 as the Central Pier, which is still in operation.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] A Heinz-owned pier named Heinz Pier was destroyed in the 1944 Great Atlantic hurricane.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The most famous Atlantic City pier was Steel Pier, which opened in 1898, and which once billed itself as "The Showplace of the Nation".
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] It closed in 1978, and was mostly destroyed in a 1982 fire.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] It was rebuilt in the late 1980s and is now operated as an amusement pier across from the Hard Rock.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Steeplechase Pier opened in 1899 and operated until 1986.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] It suffered significant damage in a 1988 fire, and the remnants of the pier were removed in 1996.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The "Steeplechase Pier Heliport" on Steel Pier is named in its honor.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Young opened "Young's Million Dollar Pier" in 1906, and on the seaward side "erected a marble mansion", fronted by a formal garden, with lighting and landscaping designed by Young's longtime friend Thomas Alva Edison.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Million Dollar Pier once rivaled Steel Pier as Atlantic City's leading pier, but after suffering decades of decline, was rebuilt into a shopping mall in the 1980s, known as "Shops on Ocean One".
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] In 2006, the Ocean One mall was bought, renovated and re-branded as "The Pier Shops at Caesars" and in 2015, it was renamed "Playground Pier".
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] In September 2023, it was renamed "ACX1 Studios" for the film and entertainment production studios that took over the building, with a planned grand reopening containing a mixture of retail, restaurants, creative space, and production studios in summer of 2024.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Garden Pier, located opposite Ocean Casino Resort, once housed a movie theater, and is now home to the Atlantic City Historical Museum.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Atlantic City has many different shopping districts and malls, many of which are located inside or adjacent to the casino resorts.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Several smaller themed retail and dining areas in casino hotels include the Borgata Shops and The Shoppes at Water Club inside Borgata, the Waterfront Shops inside of Harrah's, Spice Road inside the Trump Taj Mahal, while Resorts Casino Hotel has a small collection of stores and restaurants.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Major shopping malls are also located in and around Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Boardwalk Hall, formally known as the "Historic Atlantic City Convention Hall", is an arena in Atlantic City along the boardwalk.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Boardwalk Hall was Atlantic City's primary convention center until the opening of the Atlantic City Convention Center in 1997.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The Atlantic City Convention Center includes 500,000 sq ft (46,000 m2) of showroom space, 5 exhibit halls, 45 meeting rooms with 109,000 sq ft (10,100 m2) of space, a garage with 1,400 parking spaces, and an adjacent Sheraton hotel.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Both the Boardwalk Hall and Convention Center are operated by the Atlantic City Convention & Visitors Authority.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Atlantic City (sometimes referred to as "Monopoly City") has become well-known over the years for its portrayal in the U.S. version of the popular board game *Monopoly*, in which properties on the board are named after locations in and near Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] While the original incarnation of the game did not feature Atlantic City, it was in Indianapolis that Ruth Hoskins learned the game, and took it back to Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] After she arrived, Hoskins made a new board with Atlantic City street names, and taught it to a group of friends, who ultimately passed in on to Charles Darrow, who made some modifications to the game and claimed it as his own invention.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The relative prices of the places on the board reflect to some extent the social status of neighborhoods at the time, with wealthy white streets being worth more, and streets where Black and Asian residents lived being cheaper.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Marvin Gardens, the leading yellow property on the board, is actually a misspelling of the original location name, "Marven Gardens".
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The misspelling was said to have been introduced by Charles Todd and passed on when his home-made *Monopoly* board was copied by Charles Darrow and thence Parker Brothers.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] It was not until 1995 that Parker Brothers acknowledged this mistake and formally apologized to the residents of Marven Gardens for the misspelling, although the spelling error was not corrected.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Some of the actual locations that correspond to board elements have changed since the game's release.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Illinois Avenue was renamed Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Charles Place no longer exists, as the Showboat Casino Hotel was developed where it once ran.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The "Short Line" is believed to refer to the Shore Fast Line, a streetcar line that served Atlantic City, or a bus route.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The B&O Railroad did not serve Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] A booklet included with the reprinted 1935 edition states that the four railroads that served Atlantic City in the mid-1930s were the Jersey Central, the Seashore Lines, the Reading Railroad, and the Pennsylvania Railroad.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The actual "Electric Company" and "Water Works" serving the city are the Atlantic City Electric Company and the Atlantic City Municipal Utilities Authority, respectively.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Ever since Atlantic City's growth as a resort town, numerous attractions and tourist traps have originated in the city.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] A popular fixture in the early 20th century at the Steel Pier was horse diving, which was introduced by William "Doc" Carver.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The Steel Pier featured several other novelty attractions, including the Diving Bell, human high-divers and a water circus.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Advertisements for the Steel Pier in its heyday featured plaster sculptures set upon wooden bases along roads leading up to Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] By the end of World War II, many animal demonstrations declined in popularity after criticisms of animal abuse and neglect.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Rolling chairs were introduced in 1876 for handicapped visitors and have been in continuous use since 1887 when they were made available to the general public, and have been a boardwalk fixture ever since.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] While powered carts appeared in the 1960s, the original and most common were made of wicker.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The wicker canopied chairs-on-wheels are manually pushed the length of the boardwalk by attendants, much like a rickshaw.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Tramcars carrying 25 passengers each were introduced in June 1973, by which time the number of rolling carts had dropped from the thousands to as few as 10.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] A tram service was introduced in 2015, initially using the warning announcements that had been used on Wildwood's tramcars until it was changed after complaints from Wildwood.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The Absecon Lighthouse is a coastal lighthouse located in the South Inlet section of Atlantic City overlooking Absecon Inlet.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] It is the tallest lighthouse in the state of New Jersey and is the third tallest masonry lighthouse in the United States.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Construction began in 1854, with the light first lit on January 15, 1857.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The lighthouse was deactivated in 1933 and although the light still shines every night, it is no longer an active navigational aid.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Gardner's Basin, which is home to the Atlantic City Aquarium as well as small shops and restaurants, is located a short distance north of Absecon Light.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] While located 2 mi (3.2 km) south of Atlantic City in Margate City, Lucy the Elephant has become almost an icon for the Atlantic City area.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Lucy is a six-story elephant-shaped example of novelty architecture, constructed of wood and tin sheeting in 1882 by James V.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Lafferty in an effort to sell real estate and attract tourism.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Over the years, Lucy had served as a restaurant, business office, cottage, and tavern (the last closed by Prohibition).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Lucy had fallen into disrepair by the 1960s and was scheduled for demolition.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The structure was moved and refurbished as a result of a "Save Lucy" campaign in 1970 and received designation as a National Historic Landmark in 1976, and is open as a museum.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Atlantic City was the home of the Miss America competition, hosting the event from its inception until 2004, and again from 2013 to 2018.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The Miss America competition originated on September 7, 1921, as a two-day beauty contest, and it included state contestants as well as women from various cities around the country.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The event that year was called the "Atlantic City Pageant", and the winner of the grand prize, Margaret Gorman, took home the 3-foot Golden Mermaid trophy.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Gorman was not called "Miss America" until 1922, when she re-entered the pageant and lost to Mary Campbell.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The pageant was initiated to extend the tourist season after the Labor Day weekend.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The pageant has been nationally televised since 1954.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] It peaked in the early 1960s, when it was repeatedly the highest-rated program on American television.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] It was seen as a symbol of the United States, with Miss America often being referred to as the female equivalent of the President.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The pageant's longtime emcee, Bert Parks, hosted the event from 1955 to 1979.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] At the Atlantic City Convention Center, there is a 400 lb (180 kg) interactive statue of Parks holding a crown.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] When a visitor puts their head inside the crown, sensors activate a recorded playback of his *"There She Is..."* line through speakers hidden behind nearby bushes.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The television show *Boardwalk Empire*, an American series from cable network HBO set in Atlantic City during the Prohibition era, raised interest in the Roaring Twenties-era city.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Starring Steve Buscemi, the show was adapted from a chapter about historical criminal kingpin Enoch "Nucky" Johnson (who is renamed "Enoch Thompson" in the show) in Nelson Johnson's book, *Boardwalk Empire: The Birth, High Times, and Corruption of Atlantic City*.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The Orange Loop is a neighborhood near the beach in Atlantic City with a focus on live music establishments like Anchor Rock Club and Tennessee Beer Hall.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] It runs perpendicular from the boardwalk inland roughly to St.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] James Place, Pacific Avenue and the boardwalk, and derives its name from the orange color of those streets on a traditional Monopoly gameboard.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The Orange Loop Amphitheater hosted the Frantic City indie rock music festival on the loop in 2022.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The Atlantic City Race Course in Hamilton Township was a horse racing track that operated from 1946 to 2015.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The ShopRite LPGA Classic is an LPGA Tour women's golf tournament held near Atlantic City since it started in 1986.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Since February 2, 1887, the city of Atlantic City has seen 2,538 (as of September 2018) professional boxing fight programs, the first one being one with a main event fight between Willie Clark, 3-0-3, and debuting Horace Leeds, won by Clark on points over four rounds.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] During the 1980s, professional boxing activity boomed in Atlantic City, at times rivaling Las Vegas, Nevada, in staging major boxing fights.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Fighters who fought in Atlantic City at that era include Marvelous Marvin Hagler, Thomas Hearns, Wilfredo Gómez, Jeff Chandler, Larry Holmes, George Foreman, Mike Tyson and others.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Fights included The Brawl For it All, Tyson versus Holmes, Tyson versus Michael Spinks, and Roberto Durán versus Iran Barkley.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Many boxing matches were held at Donald Trump's Trump Plaza, promoted either by Bob Arum or Don King.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Atlantic City is one of five municipalities in the state—and the only one outside of Cape May County—that offer free public access to oceanfront beaches monitored by lifeguards, joining Wildwood, North Wildwood, Wildwood Crest and Upper Township's Strathmere section.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Atlantic City is governed within the Faulkner Act (formally known as the Optional Municipal Charter Law) under the Mayor-Council system of municipal government (Plan D), implemented by direct petition effective as of July 1, 1982.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The city is one of 71 municipalities (of the 564) statewide governed under this form.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The governing body of Atlantic City comprises the Mayor and the City Council, all elected on a partisan basis to serve four-year terms of office as part of the November general election.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The council includes nine members, who are elected on a staggered basis, with one member from each of six wards and three serving at-large.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The six ward seats are up for election together and the mayoral seat and the council at-large seats are up for vote together two years later.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The City Council exercises the legislative power of the municipality for the purpose of holding Council meetings to introduce ordinances and resolutions to regulate City government.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] In addition, Council members review budgets submitted by the Mayor; provide for an annual audit of the city's accounts and financial transactions; organize standing committees and hold public hearings to address important issues which impact Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Former Mayor Bob Levy created the Atlantic City Ethics Board in 2007, but the Board was dissolved two years later by vote of the Atlantic City Council.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] As of 2026, the Mayor is Democrat Marty Small Sr., whose term of office ends December 31, 2029.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Gilliam Jr. following his resignation on October 3, 2019.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Small initially served as mayor on an interim basis for an unexpired term ending on December 31, 2021.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Kurtz (R, 2027; 6th Ward), Maria Lacca (R, 2027; 5th Ward), Stephanie Marshall (D, 2029; At-Large), and Mohammed Suhel Ahmed (D, 2029; At-Large).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] In 2024, Democrat Muhammed "Anjum" Zia, who served as a councilman for the 5th ward, was removed from office after it was found the he did not reside in Atlantic City, but instead with his family in Egg Harbor Township.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] He was ousted from the city council, and in a court-ordered special election that November, Republican Maria Lacca, who brought about the investigation against Zia, flipped the seat, becoming the first Republican to win it since 1988.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] She became one out of two Republicans now currently on Atlantic City's council, with the other being councilman Jesse O.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] In May 2020, voters rejected by a 3–1 margin a referendum that would have changed the city to a council-manager form of government which would have reduced the size of the city council and shifted responsibility for day-to-day operation from an elected mayor to an appointed city manager.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] In December 2019, LaToya Dunston was selected from a list of three candidates nominated by the Democratic municipal committee to serve the remainder of the term of the Second Ward seat that had been held by Marty Small until he stepped down when he was appointed as mayor.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Following questions about false claims he had made about his military record, Mayor Bob Levy left City Hall in September 2007 in a city-owned vehicle for an unknown destination.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] After a 13-day absence, his lawyer revealed that Levy was in Carrier Clinic, a rehabilitation hospital.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Levy resigned in October 2007 and then-Council President William Marsh assumed the office of Mayor and served six weeks until an interim mayor was named.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Atlantic City is located in the 2nd Congressional district and is part of New Jersey's 2nd state legislative district.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] For the 119th United States Congress, New Jersey's 2nd congressional district is represented by Jeff Van Drew (R, Dennis Township).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] New Jersey is represented in the United States Senate by Democrats Cory Booker (Newark, term ends 2027) and Andy Kim (Moorestown, term ends 2031).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] For the 2026–2027 session, the 2nd legislative district of the New Jersey Legislature is represented in the New Jersey Senate by Vincent J.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Polistina (R, Egg Harbor Township) and in the General Assembly by Don Guardian (R, Atlantic City) and Maureen Rowan (D, Atlantic City).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Atlantic County is governed by a directly elected county executive and a nine-member Board of County Commissioners, responsible for legislation.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The executive serves a four-year term and the commissioners are elected to staggered three-year terms, of which four are elected from the county on an at-large basis and five of the commissioners represent equally populated districts.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] As of 2025, Atlantic County's Executive is Dennis Levinson (R, Northfield), whose term of office ends December 31, 2027.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Dase (R, District 4, including Brigantine, Galloway Township, Egg Harbor Township (part), and Port Republic; 2025, Galloway Township), Vice Chair James A.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Bertino (R, District 5-- Buena, Buena Vista Township, Corbin City, Egg Harbor City, Estell Manor, Folsom, Hamilton Township (part), Hammonton, Mullica Township and Weymouth Township; 2027, Hammonton), June Byrnes (R, At-Large; 2026, Linwood), Michael Ruffu (R, At-Large; Margate, 2027) Amy L.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Gatto (R, At-large; 2025, Hamilton Township) and John W.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Atlantic County's constitutional officers are: Clerk Joesph J.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Giralo (R, 2026, Hammonton), Sheriff Joe O'Donoghue (R, 2026, Egg Harbor Township) and Surrogate James Curcio (R, 2025, Hammonton).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] As of March 23, 2011, there were a total of 20,001 registered voters in Atlantic City, of which 12,063 (60.3% vs.
