[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Casinos operate under licenses granted by the commission.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The commission is headquartered in the Arcade Building at Tennessee Avenue and Boardwalk in Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The New Jersey Division of Gaming Enforcement is a division of the New Jersey Department of Law and Public Safety and is responsible for certifying casino gaming revenue, registering casino employees and non-gaming vendors, licensing gaming vendors, and handling all casino patron complaints.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The CRDA was founded in 1984 and is responsible for directing the spending of casino reinvestment funds in public and private projects to benefit Atlantic City and other areas of the state.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] From 1985 through April 2008, CRDA spent US$1.5 billion on projects in Atlantic City and US$300 million throughout New Jersey.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The Convention & Visitors Authority (ACCVA) was in charge of advertising and marketing for the city as well as promoting economic growth through convention and leisure tourism development.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The ACCVA managed the Boardwalk Hall and Atlantic City Convention Center, as well as the Boardwalk Welcome Center inside Boardwalk Hall and a welcome center on the Atlantic City Expressway.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] In 2011, the ACCVA was absorbed into the CRDA as part of the state takeover that created the tourism district.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The Atlantic City Special Improvement District (SID) was a nonprofit organization created in 1992, funded by a special assessment tax on businesses within the improvement district.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] It carried out various activities to improve the city's business community, including street cleaning and promotional efforts.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] In 2011, the SID was absorbed by the CRDA; the former SID boundaries would be expanded to the include all areas in the newly formed tourism district.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Under the new structure, established by state legislation, the CRDA assumed responsibility for the staff, equipment and programs of the SID.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The new SID division includes a SID committee made up of CRDA board members and an advisory council consisting of the current trustees and others.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The **Atlantic City Fire Department** (**ACFD**) provides fire protection and first responder emergency medical services to the city.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The ACFD operates out of six fire stations, located throughout the city in one battalion, under the command of a battalion chief, who in-turn reports to an on-duty Deputy Chief, or Tour Commander each shift.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The city is protected by the Atlantic City Police Department, which handles 150,000 calls per year.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] The Atlantic City School District serves students in pre-kindergarten through twelfth grades.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] As of the 2020–21 school year, the district, comprised of 11 schools, had an enrollment of 6,553 students and 617.3 classroom teachers (on an FTE basis), for a student–teacher ratio of 10.6:1.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Schools in the district (with 2020–21 enrollment data from the National Center for Education Statistics) are Venice Park School (36 students in PreK), Brighton Avenue School (315 students; in grades PreK-5), Chelsea Heights School (332; PreK-8), Dr.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] School Complex (543; PreK-8), New York Avenue School (548; PreK-8), Pennsylvania Avenue School (549; PreK-8), Richmond Avenue School (615; PreK-8), Sovereign Avenue School (696; PreK-8), Texas Avenue School (499; K-8), Uptown School Complex (536; PreK-8) and Atlantic City High School (1,771; 9–12).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Pennsylvania Avenue School opened for the 2012–13 school year, with most students shifting from New Jersey Avenue School, which had been one of the district's oldest and most rundown schools.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Students from Brigantine, Longport, Margate City and Ventnor City attend Atlantic City High School as part of sending/receiving relationships with the respective school districts.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] City public school students are also eligible to attend the Atlantic County Institute of Technology in the Mays Landing section of Hamilton Township or the Charter-Tech High School for the Performing Arts, located in Somers Point.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Oceanside Charter School, which offered pre-Kindergarten through eighth grade, was founded in 1999 and closed in June 2013 when its charter was not renewed by the New Jersey Department of Education.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Founded in 1908, Our Lady Star of the Sea Regional School is a Catholic elementary school, operates under the jurisdiction of the Diocese of Camden.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Nearby college campuses include those of Atlantic Cape Community College and Stockton University, the latter of which offers classes and resources in the city such as the Carnegie Library Center, which was turned back to the control of the city in April 2022.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] Atlantic City is part of the Philadelphia television market.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p02] There are six stations licensed in the area.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] The three roadways that enter Atlantic City are: Black Horse Pike/Harding Highway (US 322/40 via the Albany Avenue drawbridge), White Horse Pike (US 30), and the Atlantic City Expressway through the Brigantine Connector.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] Atlantic City is roughly 132 mi (212 km) south of New York City via the Garden State Parkway and 55 mi (89 km) southeast of Philadelphia.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] Atlantic City is connected to other cities in several ways.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] NJ Transit's Atlantic City Rail Terminal at the Atlantic City Convention Center provides service from 30th Street Station in Philadelphia through several smaller South Jersey communities via the Atlantic City Line.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] In June 2006, the board of NJ Transit approved a three-year trial of express train service between New York Penn Station and the Atlantic City Rail Terminal.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] The line, known as ACES (Atlantic City Express Service), ran from February 2009 to March 2012.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] The approximate travel time was 2+1⁄2 hours, with a stop at Newark Penn Station, and was part of the casinos' multimillion-dollar investments in Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] Most of the funding for the transit line was provided by Harrah's Entertainment (owners of both Harrah's Atlantic City and Caesars Atlantic City) and the Borgata, which pulled the plug after millions in losses.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] The Atlantic City Bus Terminal is the home to local, intrastate and interstate bus companies including NJ Transit, OurBus and Greyhound bus lines.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] The Greyhound Lucky Streak Express offers service to Atlantic City from New York City, Brooklyn, Philadelphia, Baltimore, and Washington, D.C.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] In addition to stopping at the Atlantic City Bus Terminal, Greyhound buses stop at various casinos in Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] Martz Trailways provides bus service to various casinos in Atlantic City from Wilkes-Barre, Scranton, and White Haven in Pennsylvania.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] Klein Transportation provides bus service to various casinos in Atlantic City from Shillington, Douglassville, Royersford, and Audubon in Pennsylvania.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] The Atlantic City Jitney Association (ACJA) offers service on four fixed-route lines and on shuttles to and from the rail terminal.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] Commercial airlines serving Atlantic City include Atlantic City International Airport, located 9 mi (14 km) northwest of the city in Egg Harbor Township.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] Many travelers also fly into Philadelphia International Airport, Trenton-Mercer Airport, or Newark Liberty International Airport, where there are wider selections of carriers from which to choose.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] The historic downtown Bader Field airport is now permanently closed and plans are in the works to redevelop the land.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] In 2022, the *CASA MAR* project was announced, a $3 billion plan to redevelop Bader Field into a mixed-use complex that includes housing and employment opportunities.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] The AtlantiCare Regional Medical Center is a health system based in Atlantic City.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] Founded in 1898, it includes two hospitals; the Atlantic City Campus and the Mainland Campus in Pomona, New Jersey.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] It has Atlantic City's only cancer institute, heart institute, and neonatal intensive care unit.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] South Jersey Industries provides natural gas to the city under the South Jersey Gas division.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] Marina Energy and its subsidiary, Energenic, a joint business venture with a long-time business partner, operate two thermal power stations in the city.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] The Marina Thermal Plant serves the Borgata while a second plant serves the Resorts Hotel and Casino.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] Another thermal plant is the Midtown Thermal Control Center on Atlantic and Ohio Avenues built by Conectiv, which opened in 1997 and provides chilled water for hotels and other facilities along the Boardwalk.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] Electrical power in Atlantic City and its immediate surrounding area is provided primarily served Atlantic City Electric, which was incorporated in 1924 and provides power from the Beesley's Point Generating Station in Upper Township and other locations.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] The Jersey-Atlantic Wind Farm, opened in 2005, is the first onshore coastal wind farm in the United States.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] In October 2010, North American Offshore Wind Conference was held in the city and included tours of the facility and potential sites for further development.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] In February 2011, the state passed legislation permitting the construction of windmills for electricity along pre-existing piers, such as the Steel Pier.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/atlantic-city-p03] The first phase of the Atlantic Wind Connection, a planned electrical transmission backbone along the Jersey Shore was planned to be operational in 2013.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The term *biotechnology* was first used by Károly Ereky in 1919 to refer to the production of products from raw materials with the aid of living organisms.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The core principle of biotechnology involves harnessing biological systems and organisms, such as bacteria, yeast, and plants, to perform specific tasks or produce valuable substances.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology has had a significant impact on many areas of society, from medicine to agriculture to environmental science.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] One of the key techniques used in biotechnology is genetic engineering, which allows scientists to modify the genetic makeup of organisms to achieve desired outcomes.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] This can involve inserting genes from one organism into another, and consequently, creating new traits or modifying existing ones.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Other important techniques used in biotechnology include tissue culture, which allows researchers to grow cells and tissues in the lab for research and medical purposes, and fermentation, which is used to produce a wide range of products such as beer, wine, and cheese.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The applications of biotechnology are diverse and have led to the development of products like drugs, biofuels, genetically modified crops, and innovative materials.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] It has also been used to address environmental challenges, such as developing biodegradable plastics and using microorganisms to clean up contaminated sites.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] As a result, there is ongoing debate and regulation surrounding the use and application of biotechnology in various industries and fields.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology encompasses a wide range of procedures for modifying living organisms for human purposes, going back to domestication of animals, the cultivation of plants, and "improvements" to these through breeding programs that employ artificial selection and hybridization.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Modern usage also includes genetic engineering, as well as cell and tissue culture technologies.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The American Chemical Society defines *biotechnology* as the application of biological organisms, systems, or processes by various industries to learning about the science of life and the improvement of the value of materials and organisms, such as pharmaceuticals, crops, and livestock.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] As per the European Federation of Biotechnology, biotechnology is the integration of natural science and organisms, cells, parts thereof, and molecular analogues for products and services.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology is based on the basic biological sciences (e.g., molecular biology, biochemistry, cell biology, embryology, genetics, microbiology) and conversely provides methods to support and perform basic research in biology.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The utilization of biological processes, organisms or systems to produce products that are anticipated to improve human lives is termed biotechnology.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] By contrast, bioengineering is generally thought of as a related field that more heavily emphasizes higher systems approaches (not necessarily the altering or using of biological materials *directly*) for interfacing with and utilizing living things.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Bioengineering is the application of the principles of engineering and natural sciences to tissues, cells, and molecules.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] This can be considered as the use of knowledge from working with and manipulating biology to achieve a result that can improve functions in plants and animals.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Relatedly, biomedical engineering is an overlapping field that often draws upon and applies *biotechnology* (by various definitions), especially in certain sub-fields of biomedical or chemical engineering such as tissue engineering, biopharmaceutical engineering, and genetic engineering.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Many forms of human-derived agriculture fit the broad definition of "utilizing a biotechnological system to make products".
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The cultivation of plants may be viewed as the earliest biotechnological enterprise.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Agriculture has been theorized to have become the dominant way of producing food since the Neolithic Revolution.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Through early biotechnology, the earliest farmers selected and bred the best-suited crops (e.g., those with the highest yields) to produce enough food to support a growing population.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] As crops and fields became increasingly large and difficult to maintain, it was discovered that specific organisms and their by-products could effectively fertilize, restore nitrogen, and control pests.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Throughout the history of agriculture, farmers have inadvertently altered the genetics of their crops through introducing them to new environments and breeding them with other plants — one of the first forms of biotechnology.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] These processes were also included in the early fermentation of beer.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] These processes were introduced in early Mesopotamia, Egypt, China and India, and still use the same basic biological methods.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] In brewing, malted grains (containing enzymes) convert starch from grains into sugar and then adding specific yeasts to produce beer.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] In this process, carbohydrates in the grains broke down into alcohols, such as ethanol.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Later, other cultures developed the process of lactic acid fermentation, which produced other preserved foods, such as soy sauce.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Fermentation was also used in this time period to produce leavened bread.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Although the process of fermentation was not fully understood until Louis Pasteur's work in 1857, it is still the first use of biotechnology to convert a food source into another form.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Before the time of Charles Darwin's work and life, animal and plant scientists had already used selective breeding.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Darwin added to that body of work with his scientific observations about the ability of science to change species.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] These accounts contributed to Darwin's theory of natural selection.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] For thousands of years, humans have used selective breeding to improve the production of crops and livestock to use them for food.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] In selective breeding, organisms with desirable characteristics are mated to produce offspring with the same characteristics.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] For example, this technique was used with corn to produce the largest and sweetest crops.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] In the early twentieth century scientists gained a greater understanding of microbiology and explored ways of manufacturing specific products.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] In 1917, Chaim Weizmann first used a pure microbiological culture in an industrial process, that of manufacturing corn starch using *Clostridium acetobutylicum,* to produce acetone, which the United Kingdom desperately needed to manufacture explosives during World War I.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology has also led to the development of antibiotics.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] In 1928, Alexander Fleming discovered the mold *Penicillium*.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] His work led to the purification of the antibiotic formed by the mold by Howard Florey, Ernst Boris Chain and Norman Heatley – to form what we today know as penicillin.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] In 1940, penicillin became available for medicinal use to treat bacterial infections in humans.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The field of modern biotechnology is generally thought of as having been born in 1971 when Paul Berg's (Stanford) experiments in gene splicing had early success.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Cohen (Stanford) significantly advanced the new technology in 1972 by transferring genetic material into a bacterium, such that the imported material would be reproduced.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The commercial viability of a biotechnology industry was significantly expanded on June 16, 1980, when the United States Supreme Court ruled that a genetically modified microorganism could be patented in the case of *Diamond v.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Indian-born Ananda Chakrabarty, working for General Electric, had modified a bacterium (of the genus *Pseudomonas*) capable of breaking down crude oil, which he proposed to use in treating oil spills.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] (Chakrabarty's work did not involve gene manipulation but rather the transfer of entire organelles between strains of the *Pseudomonas* bacterium).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The MOSFET was invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960, Two years later, Leland C.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Clark and Champ Lyons invented the first biosensor in 1962.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Biosensor MOSFETs were later developed, and they have since been widely used to measure physical, chemical, biological and environmental parameters.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The first BioFET was the ion-sensitive field-effect transistor (ISFET), invented by Piet Bergveld in 1970.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] It is a special type of MOSFET, where the metal gate is replaced by an ion-sensitive membrane, electrolyte solution and reference electrode.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The ISFET is widely used in biomedical applications, such as the detection of DNA hybridization, biomarker detection from blood, antibody detection, glucose measurement, pH sensing, and genetic technology.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] By the mid-1980s, other BioFETs had been developed, including the gas sensor FET (GASFET), pressure sensor FET (PRESSFET), chemical field-effect transistor (ChemFET), reference ISFET (REFET), enzyme-modified FET (ENFET) and immunologically modified FET (IMFET).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] By the early 2000s, BioFETs such as the DNA field-effect transistor (DNAFET), gene-modified FET (GenFET) and cell-potential BioFET (CPFET) had been developed.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] A factor influencing the biotechnology sector's success is improved intellectual property rights legislation—and enforcement—worldwide, as well as strengthened demand for medical and pharmaceutical products.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Rising demand for biofuels is expected to be good news for the biotechnology sector, with the Department of Energy estimating ethanol usage could reduce U.S. petroleum-derived fuel consumption by up to 30% by 2030.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The biotechnology sector has allowed the U.S. farming industry to rapidly increase its supply of corn and soybeans—the main inputs into biofuels—by developing genetically modified seeds that resist pests and drought.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] By increasing farm productivity, biotechnology boosts biofuel production.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology has applications in four major industrial areas, including health care (medical), crop production and agriculture, non-food (industrial) uses of crops and other products (e.g., biodegradable plastics, vegetable oil, biofuels), and environmental uses.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] For example, one application of biotechnology is the directed use of microorganisms for the manufacture of organic products (examples include beer and milk products).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Another example is using naturally present bacteria by the mining industry in bioleaching.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology is also used to recycle, treat waste, clean up sites contaminated by industrial activities (bioremediation), and also to produce biological weapons.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] In medicine, modern biotechnology has many applications in areas such as pharmaceutical drug discoveries and production, pharmacogenomics, and genetic testing (or genetic screening).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] In 2021, nearly 40% of the total company value of pharmaceutical biotech companies worldwide were active in Oncology with Neurology and Rare Diseases being the other two big applications.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Pharmacogenomics (a combination of pharmacology and genomics) is the technology that analyses how genetic makeup affects an individual's response to drugs.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Researchers in the field investigate the influence of genetic variation on drug responses in patients by correlating gene expression or single-nucleotide polymorphisms with a drug's efficacy or toxicity.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The purpose of pharmacogenomics is to develop rational means to optimize drug therapy, with respect to the patients' genotype, to ensure maximum efficacy with minimal adverse effects.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Such approaches promise the advent of "personalized medicine"; in which drugs and drug combinations are optimized for each individual's unique genetic makeup.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology has contributed to the discovery and manufacturing of traditional small molecule pharmaceutical drugs as well as drugs that are the product of biotechnology – biopharmaceutics.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Modern biotechnology can be used to manufacture existing medicines relatively easily and cheaply.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The first genetically engineered products were medicines designed to treat human diseases.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] To cite one example, in 1978 Genentech developed synthetic humanized insulin by joining its gene with a plasmid vector inserted into the bacterium *Escherichia coli*.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Insulin, widely used for the treatment of diabetes, was previously extracted from the pancreas of abattoir animals (cattle or pigs).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The genetically engineered bacteria are able to produce large quantities of synthetic human insulin at relatively low cost.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology has also enabled emerging therapeutics like gene therapy.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Genetic testing allows the genetic diagnosis of vulnerabilities to inherited diseases, and can also be used to determine a child's parentage (genetic mother and father) or in general a person's ancestry.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] In addition to studying chromosomes to the level of individual genes, genetic testing in a broader sense includes biochemical tests for the possible presence of genetic diseases, or mutant forms of genes associated with increased risk of developing genetic disorders.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Genetic testing identifies changes in chromosomes, genes, or proteins.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Most of the time, testing is used to find changes that are associated with inherited disorders.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The results of a genetic test can confirm or rule out a suspected genetic condition or help determine a person's chance of developing or passing on a genetic disorder.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] As of 2011 several hundred genetic tests were in use.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Since genetic testing may open up ethical or psychological problems, genetic testing is often accompanied by genetic counseling.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Genetically modified crops ("GM crops", or "biotech crops") are plants used in agriculture, the DNA of which has been modified with genetic engineering techniques.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] In most cases, the main aim is to introduce a new trait that does not occur naturally in the species.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology firms can contribute to future food security by improving the nutrition and viability of urban agriculture.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Furthermore, the protection of intellectual property rights encourages private sector investment in agrobiotechnology.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Examples in food crops include resistance to certain pests, diseases, stressful environmental conditions, resistance to chemical treatments (e.g. resistance to a herbicide), reduction of spoilage, or improving the nutrient profile of the crop.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Examples in non-food crops include production of pharmaceutical agents, biofuels, and other industrially useful goods, as well as for bioremediation.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Farmers have widely adopted GM technology.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Between 1996 and 2011, the total surface area of land cultivated with GM crops had increased by a factor of 94, from 17,000 to 1,600,000 square kilometers (4,200,000 to 395,400,000 acres).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] 10% of the world's crop lands were planted with GM crops in 2010.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] As of 2011, 11 different transgenic crops were grown commercially on 395 million acres (160 million hectares) in 29 countries such as the US, Brazil, Argentina, India, Canada, China, Paraguay, Pakistan, South Africa, Uruguay, Bolivia, Australia, Philippines, Myanmar, Burkina Faso, Mexico, and Spain.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Genetically modified foods are foods produced from organisms that have had specific changes introduced into their DNA with the methods of genetic engineering.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] These techniques have allowed for the introduction of new crop traits as well as a far greater control over a food's genetic structure than previously afforded by methods such as selective breeding and mutation breeding.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Commercial sale of genetically modified foods began in 1994, when Calgene first marketed its Flavr Savr delayed ripening tomato.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] To date most genetic modification of foods have primarily focused on cash crops in high demand by farmers such as soybean, corn, canola, and cotton seed oil.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] These have been engineered for resistance to pathogens and herbicides and better nutrient profiles.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] GM livestock have also been experimentally developed; in November 2013 none were available on the market, but in 2015 the FDA approved the first GM salmon for commercial production and consumption.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] There is a scientific consensus that currently available food derived from GM crops poses no greater risk to human health than conventional food, but that each GM food needs to be tested on a case-by-case basis before introduction.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Nonetheless, members of the public are much less likely than scientists to perceive GM foods as safe.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The legal and regulatory status of GM foods varies by country, with some nations banning or restricting them, and others permitting them with widely differing degrees of regulation.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] GM crops also provide a number of ecological benefits, if not used in excess.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Insect-resistant crops have proven to lower pesticide usage, therefore reducing the environmental impact of pesticides as a whole.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology has several applications in the realm of food security.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Crops like Golden rice are engineered to have higher nutritional content, and there is potential for food products with longer shelf lives.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Though not a form of agricultural biotechnology, vaccines can help prevent diseases found in animal agriculture.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Additionally, agricultural biotechnology can expedite breeding processes in order to yield faster results and provide greater quantities of food.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Transgenic biofortification in cereals has been considered as a promising method to combat malnutrition in India and other countries.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Industrial biotechnology (known mainly in Europe as white biotechnology) is the application of biotechnology for industrial purposes, including industrial fermentation.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] It includes the practice of using cells such as microorganisms, or components of cells like enzymes, to generate industrially useful products in sectors such as chemicals, food and feed, detergents, paper and pulp, textiles and biofuels.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] In the current decades, significant progress has been done in creating genetically modified organisms (GMOs) that enhance the diversity of applications and economical viability of industrial biotechnology.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] By using renewable raw materials to produce a variety of chemicals and fuels, industrial biotechnology is actively advancing towards lowering greenhouse gas emissions and moving away from a petrochemical-based economy.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Synthetic biology is considered one of the essential cornerstones in industrial biotechnology due to its financial and sustainable contribution to the manufacturing sector.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Jointly biotechnology and synthetic biology play a crucial role in generating cost-effective products with nature-friendly features by using bio-based production instead of fossil-based.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Synthetic biology can be used to engineer model microorganisms, such as *Escherichia coli*, by genome editing tools to enhance their ability to produce bio-based products, such as bioproduction of medicines and biofuels.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] For instance, *E. coli* and *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* in a consortium could be used as industrial microbes to produce precursors of the chemotherapeutic agent paclitaxel by applying the metabolic engineering in a co-culture approach to exploit the benefits from the two microbes.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Another example of synthetic biology applications in industrial biotechnology is the re-engineering of the metabolic pathways of *E. coli* by CRISPR and CRISPRi systems toward the production of a chemical known as 1,4-butanediol, which is used in fiber manufacturing.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] In order to produce 1,4-butanediol, the authors alter the metabolic regulation of the *Escherichia coli* by CRISPR to induce point mutation in the *glt*A gene, knockout of the *sad* gene, and knock-in six genes (*cat*1, *suc*D, *4hbd*, *cat*2, *bld*, and *bdh*).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Whereas CRISPRi system used to knockdown the three competing genes (*gab*D, *ybg*C, and *tes*B) that affect the biosynthesis pathway of 1,4-butanediol.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Consequently, the yield of 1,4-butanediol significantly increased from 0.9 to 1.8 g/L.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Environmental biotechnology includes various disciplines that play an essential role in reducing environmental waste and providing environmentally safe processes, such as biofiltration and biodegradation.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The environment can be affected by biotechnologies, both positively and adversely.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Cleaning up environmental wastes is an example of an application of environmental biotechnology; whereas loss of biodiversity or loss of containment of a harmful microbe are examples of environmental implications of biotechnology.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Many cities have installed CityTrees, which use biotechnology to filter pollutants from urban atmospheres.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] There are differences in the regulation of GMOs between countries, with some of the most marked differences occurring between the US and Europe.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Regulation varies in a given country depending on the intended use of the products of the genetic engineering.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] For example, a crop not intended for food use is generally not reviewed by authorities responsible for food safety.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The European Union differentiates between approval for cultivation within the EU and approval for import and processing.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] While only a few GMOs have been approved for cultivation in the EU a number of GMOs have been approved for import and processing.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The cultivation of GMOs has triggered a debate about the coexistence of GM and non-GM crops.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Depending on the coexistence regulations, incentives for the cultivation of GM crops differ.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] The EUginius (European GMO Initiative for a Unified Database System) database is intended to help companies, interested private users and competent authorities to find precise information on the presence, detection and identification of GMOs used in the European Union.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] In 1988, after prompting from the United States Congress, the National Institute of General Medical Sciences (National Institutes of Health) (NIGMS) instituted a funding mechanism for biotechnology training.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Universities nationwide compete for these funds to establish Biotechnology Training Programs (BTPs).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Each successful application is generally funded for five years then must be competitively renewed.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Graduate students in turn compete for acceptance into a BTP; if accepted, then stipend, tuition and health insurance support are provided for two or three years during the course of their PhD thesis work.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Nineteen institutions offer NIGMS supported BTPs.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p01] Biotechnology training is also offered at undergraduate level and in community colleges.
