[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] Currently available transgenic crops and foods derived from them have been judged safe to eat and the methods used to test their safety have been deemed appropriate.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] These conclusions represent the consensus of the scientific evidence surveyed by the ICSU (2003) and they are consistent with the views of the World Health Organization (WHO, 2002).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] These foods have been assessed for increased risks to human health by several national regulatory authorities (inter alia, Argentina, Brazil, Canada, China, the United Kingdom and the United States) using their national food safety procedures (ICSU).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] To date no verifiable untoward toxic or nutritionally deleterious effects resulting from the consumption of foods derived from genetically modified crops have been discovered anywhere in the world (GM Science Review Panel).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] "Plant Genetics, Sustainable Agriculture and Global Food Security".
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] There is broad scientific consensus that genetically engineered crops currently on the market are safe to eat.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] But see also:*Domingo, José L.; Bordonaba, Jordi Giné (2011).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] "A literature review on the safety assessment of genetically modified plants" (PDF).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] In spite of this, the number of studies specifically focused on safety assessment of GM plants is still limited.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] Moreover, it is worth mentioning that most of the studies demonstrating that GM foods are as nutritional and safe as those obtained by conventional breeding, have been performed by biotechnology companies or associates, which are also responsible of commercializing these GM plants.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] Anyhow, this represents a notable advance in comparison with the lack of studies published in recent years in scientific journals by those companies.**Krimsky, Sheldon (2015).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] "An Illusory Consensus behind GMO Health Assessment".
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] I began this article with the testimonials from respected scientists that there is literally no scientific controversy over the health effects of GMOs.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] My investigation into the scientific literature tells another story.*And contrast:*Panchin, Alexander Y.; Tuzhikov, Alexander I.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] "Published GMO studies find no evidence of harm when corrected for multiple comparisons".
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] Here, we show that a number of articles some of which have strongly and negatively influenced the public opinion on GM crops and even provoked political actions, such as GMO embargo, share common flaws in the statistical evaluation of the data.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] Having accounted for these flaws, we conclude that the data presented in these articles does not provide any substantial evidence of GMO harm.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] The presented articles suggesting possible harm of GMOs received high public attention.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] However, despite their claims, they actually weaken the evidence for the harm and lack of substantial equivalency of studied GMOs.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] We emphasize that with over 1783 published articles on GMOs over the last 10 years it is expected that some of them should have reported undesired differences between GMOs and conventional crops even if no such differences exist in reality.*and*Yang, Y.T.; Chen, B.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] "Governing GMOs in the USA: science, law and public health".
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] *Journal of the Science of Food and Agriculture*.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] It is therefore not surprising that efforts to require labeling and to ban GMOs have been a growing political issue in the USA *(citing Domingo and Bordonaba, 2011)*.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] Overall, a broad scientific consensus holds that currently marketed GM food poses no greater risk than conventional food...
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] Major national and international science and medical associations have stated that no adverse human health effects related to GMO food have been reported or substantiated in peer-reviewed literature to date.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] Despite various concerns, today, the American Association for the Advancement of Science, the World Health Organization, and many independent international science organizations agree that GMOs are just as safe as other foods.
