[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] Several scientific organizations in the US have issued studies or statements regarding the safety of GMOs indicating that there is no evidence that GMOs present unique safety risks compared to conventionally bred products.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] These include the National Research Council, the American Association for the Advancement of Science, and the American Medical Association.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] Groups in the US opposed to GMOs include some environmental organizations, organic farming organizations, and consumer organizations.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] *National Academies Of Sciences, Engineering; Division on Earth Life Studies; Board on Agriculture Natural Resources; Committee on Genetically Engineered Crops: Past Experience Future Prospects (2016).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] *Genetically Engineered Crops: Experiences and Prospects*.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] The National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine (US). p.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] Archived from the original on November 16, 2021.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] *"Frequently asked questions on genetically modified foods".
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] Archived from the original on November 4, 2020.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] Different GM organisms include different genes inserted in different ways.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] This means that individual GM foods and their safety should be assessed on a case-by-case basis and that it is not possible to make general statements on the safety of all GM foods.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] GM foods currently available on the international market have passed safety assessments and are not likely to present risks for human health.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] In addition, no effects on human health have been shown as a result of the consumption of such foods by the general population in the countries where they have been approved.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] "Codex guidelines for GM foods include the analysis of unintended effects".
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] Some medical organizations, including the British Medical Association, advocate further caution based upon the precautionary principle: *"Genetically modified foods and health: a second interim statement" (PDF).
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] In our view, the potential for GM foods to cause harmful health effects is very small and many of the concerns expressed apply with equal vigour to conventionally derived foods.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] However, safety concerns cannot, as yet, be dismissed completely on the basis of information currently available.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] When seeking to optimise the balance between benefits and risks, it is prudent to err on the side of caution and, above all, learn from accumulating knowledge and experience.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] Any new technology such as genetic modification must be examined for possible benefits and risks to human health and the environment.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] As with all novel foods, safety assessments in relation to GM foods must be made on a case-by-case basis.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] Members of the GM jury project were briefed on various aspects of genetic modification by a diverse group of acknowledged experts in the relevant subjects.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] The GM jury reached the conclusion that the sale of GM foods currently available should be halted and the moratorium on commercial growth of GM crops should be continued.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] These conclusions were based on the precautionary principle and lack of evidence of any benefit.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] The Jury expressed concern over the impact of GM crops on farming, the environment, food safety and other potential health effects.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] "Public and Scientists' Views on Science and Society".
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/biotechnology-p02] The largest differences between the public and the AAAS scientists are found in beliefs about the safety of eating genetically modified (GM) foods.
