[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-a-catlin] He was born in Burlington, Vermont, and graduated from the University of Vermont in 1872.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-a-catlin] He was a chemist at the Rumford Chemical Works in Providence, Rhode Island, for forty years and the inventor of chemical processes for phosphates.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-a-catlin] He was a charter member of the American Institute of Chemical Engineers.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-a-catlin] He was an active member of the Central Congregational Church in Providence, Rhode Island.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-a-catlin] He wrote "Baking Powders: A Treatise" published by Rumford Chemical Works in 1899.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-a-catlin] In 1887, he analyzed samples relating to the Sylvester Manor on Shelter Island.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] Reese was born in Baltimore, Maryland, in 1862.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] He attended the University of Virginia for his undergraduate career.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] Upon graduation he was admitted to the University of Heidelberg in Heidelberg, Germany in 1884.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] While attending Heidelberg he was a student of Robert Bunsen.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] He received his Ph.D. in chemistry in 1886.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] Reese's undergraduate degree was granted by the University of Virginia in 1884.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] He moved to Germany for his graduate studies.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] A student of Robert Bunsen at Heidelberg University and Viktor Meyer at the University of Göttingen, Reese completed his PhD in 1886.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] Reese returned to the United States and took a position as an assistant in chemistry at Johns Hopkins University, which he held until 1888.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] After a brief tenure of only one year as professor of chemistry at Wake Forest College, he became a professor at The Citadel, The Military College of South Carolina, where he taught for eight years.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] He returned to teach at Hopkins for another four years until turning to industrial chemistry in 1900.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1922.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] In 1900, Reese took a position as chief chemist at The New Jersey Zinc Company.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] While there, he focused primarily on the contact process of sulfuric acid, developing it to a satisfactory working basis.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] As a result he drew the attention of the DuPont Company in 1902 and was appointed chief chemist.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] He established the Eastern Laboratory and was made director.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] In 1906 he was placed in direct control of the chemical division of the high explosives operative department.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] Promoted to chemical director of DuPont in 1911, he oversaw the development of new processes for creating raw materials needed for military explosives in World War I.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] During his tenure with DuPont, Reese was an instrumental player in the development of research and development practices at the company.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] Under his command as chemical director, multiple labs were centralized and organized into a two-prong strategy.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] Eastern Laboratory (Reese's original posting within DuPont) would focus on short term projects which could rapidly respond (and profit) to the demands of the market.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] In contrast, the Experimental Station would focus on long term, potentially risky projects.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] He defended the lack of immediate profitability by the Experimental Station, claiming it brought "enormous, though intangible, rewards" to DuPont.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] This belief lead to his decision regarding "complete and detailed" information on smokeless powder and refusal to break apart the research labs, despite pressure from Congress and the company.
[src:american-institute-of-chemical-engineers/charles-lee-reese] Reese retired from the board of DuPont on January 1, 1931.
